data.content:
MSTest has `CollectionAssert` and specific assert methods that give much better failure messages than `Assert.IsTrue`. Here's the improved version:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Use Assert.AreEqual for exact counts — shows expected vs actual on failure
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // Use CollectionAssert for collection-level checks
    CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);

    // Assert.IsTrue is fine for predicate checks, but pair with a message
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "Expected all users to be active");

    // Use Assert.IsNotNull instead of != null
    var admin = users.SingleOrDefault(u => u.Role == "Admin");
    Assert.IsNotNull(admin, "Expected an Admin user");
}
```

**Key improvements:**

| Instead of | Use | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count > 0)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, count)` | Shows `Expected:3 Actual:0` on failure |
| `Assert.IsTrue(x != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(x)` | Clearer failure message |
| `Assert.IsTrue(a == b)` | `Assert.AreEqual(a, b)` | Shows both values on failure |

**Other useful `CollectionAssert` methods:**
- `CollectionAssert.Contains(list, item)` — membership check
- `CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expected, actual)` — same order & elements
- `CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual)` — same elements, any order
- `CollectionAssert.IsSubsetOf(subset, superset)`

The general rule: prefer the **most specific assert** available. `Assert.IsTrue` loses all context on failure — you just get `"Expected: True, Actual: False"`.
